# Salesforce Logging & Monitoring — Implementation & Test Plan

---

## Overview

Connect Salesforce to Microsoft Defender for Cloud Apps (DfCA) to monitor security events across four threat categories: anomalous access, data theft, privilege escalation, and security policy tampering. DfCA pulls Salesforce logs automatically, analyses them, and raises alerts when something looks wrong.

**MVP scope:** Get the integration running, validate logs are flowing, configure alerts, then assess whether Salesforce Shield is needed for remaining gaps.

---

## Setup

### Prerequisites

| Requirement | Where to Check |
|---|---|
| Salesforce System Administrator access | Ask your Salesforce admin |
| Microsoft 365 Security Admin or Global Admin rights | Azure AD / Entra ID portal |
| Defender for Cloud Apps licence active | Microsoft 365 admin centre > Licences |
| Dedicated Salesforce service account (System Admin profile) | Create one before starting — do not use a personal admin account |

---

### Step 1 — Connect Salesforce to Defender for Cloud Apps

1. Go to `https://security.microsoft.com`
2. Navigate to **Cloud Apps > Connected Apps > App Connectors**
3. Click **"+ Connect an App"** → search for and select **Salesforce**
4. Click **"Connect Salesforce"** → authenticate using the dedicated service account
5. On the Salesforce OAuth consent screen, click **Allow**
6. Wait up to 60 minutes
7. Verify status shows **"Connected"** on the App Connectors page
8. Verify Salesforce appears under **Setup > Apps > Connected Apps > Manage Connected Apps** in Salesforce

---

### Step 2 — Enable Built-in Policies

In Defender, go to **Cloud Apps > Policies > Policy Management** and enable each of these:

| Policy Name | Set Severity To |
|---|---|
| Impossible Travel | High |
| Activity from Anonymous IP | High |
| Multiple Failed Login Attempts | High |
| Mass Download by a Single User | High |
| Admin Activity | Medium |
| Terminated User Activity | Critical |

For each: click the policy → set to **Enabled** → confirm Salesforce is in scope → save.

---

### Step 3 — Create Custom Policies

In Defender, go to **Cloud Apps > Policies > Policy Management > Create Policy > Activity Policy** for each below:

| Policy Name | Filters | Severity |
|---|---|---|
| SF - Breakglass Account Login | App = Salesforce, Activity = Login, User = [breakglass usernames] | High |
| SF - Suspicious User Agent | App = Salesforce, User Agent not containing: Mozilla, Chrome, Safari, Edge, Firefox | Medium |
| SF - Bulk API Data Request | App = Salesforce, Activity = Bulk API job, Count > 5 within 1 hour per user | High |
| SF - Bulk Deletion Operation | App = Salesforce, Activity = Delete, Count > 50 within 30 minutes per user | High |
| SF - New Admin Account Created | App = Salesforce, Activity = Create User, Profile = System Administrator | High |
| SF - Any New User Created | App = Salesforce, Activity = Create User | Medium |
| SF - Permission Modification | App = Salesforce, Activity = Permission Set Assignment or Profile Change | High |
| SF - User Account Enabled/Disabled | App = Salesforce, Activity = User Activated or User Deactivated | High (activate) / Medium (deactivate) |
| SF - MFA Disabled on Account | App = Salesforce, Activity = Identity Verification settings change | High |
| SF - Audit Logging Config Changed | App = Salesforce, Activity = Debug Log or Event Monitoring settings change | Critical |
| SF - Security Policy Changed | App = Salesforce, Activity = Sharing Settings, Session Settings, Password Policy, or IP Restriction change | High |

---

### Step 4 — Configure Alert Notifications

1. In Defender, go to **Settings > Cloud Apps > Mail Settings** — set the security team email as the alert recipient
2. For Critical severity policies, add a secondary escalation contact
3. Optionally connect to a Microsoft Teams channel via **Settings > Microsoft Teams integration**

